docs.title: Channel
docs.description: Represents a context channel that applications can join to share context data and provides functions for interacting with it.

docs.title: DesktopAgent
docs.description: An FDC3 Desktop Agent is a desktop component (or aggregate of components) that serves as an orchestrator for applications in its domain.

docs.title: Errors
docs.description: FDC3 API operations may sometimes result in an error, which must be returned to the caller. Errors should be returned by rejecting the promise returned by the API with a JavaScript Error object (or equivalent for the language of the implementation). The Error Object's message should be chosen from the appropriate Error enumeration below.

docs.title: Globals
docs.description: Since FDC3 is typically available to the whole web application, desktop agents are expected to make the DesktopAgent interface available at a global level.

docs.title: Metadata
docs.description: FDC3 API operations return various types of metadata.

docs.title: PrivateChannel
docs.description: Object representing a private context channel, which is intended to support secure communication between applications, and extends the Channel interface with event handlers which provide information on the connection state of both parties, ensuring that desktop agents do not need to queue or retain messages that are broadcast before a context listener is added and that applications are able to stop broadcasting messages when the other party has disconnected.

docs.title: Types
docs.description: FDC3 API operations make use of several type declarations.

docs.title: API Overview (next)
docs.description: The role of FDC3 API is to establish a baseline interface for interoperability between applications. Because FDC3 is largely an agreement between existing platforms and applications, standards should be optimized for ease of adoption rather than functional completeness. Functionality absent from a FDC3 specification is in no way a commentary on its importance.

docs.title: Context Data (next)
docs.description: To interoperate, apps need to exchange commonly recognized context structures that can indicate topic with any number of identifiers or mappings to different systems. FDC3 Context Data defines a standard for passing common identifiers and data between apps to create a seamless workflow. docs.title: API Specification 1.0
docs.description: Components

docs.title: Context
docs.description: The base object that all contexts should extend.

docs.title: DesktopAgent
docs.description: A Desktop Agent is a desktop component (or aggregate of components) that serves as a launcher and message router (broker) for applications in its domain.

docs.description: OpenError

docs.title: API Overview
docs.description: The API specification of the FDC3 standard support the following goals:

docs.title: AppIntent
docs.description: An interface that represents the binding of an intent to apps, returned as part of intent disocvery.

docs.title: AppMetadata
docs.description: App metadata is provided by the FDC3 App Directory that the desktop agent connects to.

docs.title: Channel
docs.description: Represents a context channel that applications can use to send and receive context data.

docs.title: ChannelError
docs.description: Contains constants representing the errors that can be encountered when calling channels using the joinChannel or getOrCreateChannel methods, or the getCurrentContext, broadcast or addContextListener methods on the Channel object.

docs.title: Context
docs.description: The base object that all contexts should extend.

docs.title: ContextHandler
docs.description: Describes a callback that handles a context event.

docs.title: DesktopAgent
docs.description: An FDC3 Desktop Agent is a desktop component (or aggregate of components) that serves as an orchestrator for applications in its domain.

docs.title: DisplayMetadata
docs.description: A desktop agent (typically for system channels) may want to provide additional information about how a channel can be represented in a UI. A common use case is for color linking.

docs.title: Errors
docs.description: Some FDC3 API operations return promises that can result in errors.

docs.title: Globals
docs.description: Since FDC3 is typically available to the whole web application, desktop agents are expected to make the DesktopAgent interface available at a global level.

docs.title: IntentMetadata
docs.description: The Interface used to describe an Intent within the platform.

docs.title: IntentResolution
docs.description: IntentResolution provides a standard format for data returned upon resolving an intent.

docs.title: Listener
docs.description: A Listener object is returned when an application subscribes to intents or context broadcasts via the addIntentListener or addContextListener methods on the DesktopAgent object.

docs.title: Metadata
docs.description: FDC3 API operations return various types of metadata.

docs.title: OpenError
docs.description: Contains constants representing the errors that can be encountered when calling the open method on the DesktopAgent object.

docs.title: ResolveError
docs.description: Contains constants representing the errors that can be encountered when calling the findIntent or findIntentsByContext methods on the DesktopAgent.

Apps are registered with a declaration of the intents and context data that can be used when interoperating.

docs.description: FDC3 API standards support the following goals:

docs.title: AppIntent
docs.description: An interface that represents the binding of an intent to apps, returned as part of intent disocvery.

docs.title: AppMetadata
docs.description: App metadata is provided by the FDC3 App Directory that the desktop agent connects to.

docs.title: Channel
docs.description: Represents a context channel that applications can join to share context data.

docs.title: ChannelError
docs.description: Contains constants representing the errors that can be encountered when calling channels using the joinChannel or getOrCreateChannel methods, or the getCurrentContext, broadcast or addContextListener methods on the Channel object.

docs.title: Context
docs.description: The base object that all contexts should extend.

docs.title: ContextHandler
docs.description: Describes a callback that handles a context event.

docs.title: DesktopAgent
docs.description: A Desktop Agent is a desktop component (or aggregate of components) that serves as a launcher and message router (broker) for applications in its domain.

docs.title: DisplayMetadata
docs.description: A desktop agent (typically for system channels) may want to provide additional information about how a channel can be represented in a UI. A common use case is for color linking.

docs.title: IntentMetadata
docs.description: The Interface used to describe an Intent within the platform.

docs.title: IntentResolution
docs.description: IntentResolution provides a standard format for data returned upon resolving an intent.

docs.title: Listener
docs.description: A Listener object is returned when an application subscribes to intents or context broadcasts via the addIntentListener or addContextListener methods on the DesktopAgent object.

docs.title: OpenError
docs.description: Contains constants representing the errors that can be encountered when calling the open method on the DesktopAgent object.

docs.title: ResolveError
docs.description: Contains constants representing the errors that can be encountered when calling the findIntent or findIntentsByContext methods on the DesktopAgent.

docs.description: The FDC3 App Directory provides trusted identity for financial desktop apps. Apps are registered with a declaration of the intents and context data that can be used when interoperating.

docs.description: Why look for FDC3 enabled applications?

docs.title: API Overview
docs.description: FDC3 API standards support the following goals:

docs.title: API Specification 1.0
docs.description: Components

docs.title: Context
docs.description: The base object that all contexts should extend.

docs.title: DesktopAgent
docs.description: A Desktop Agent is a desktop component (or aggregate of components) that serves as a launcher and message router (broker) for applications in its domain.

docs.title: Errors
docs.description: OpenError

docs.title: Channel
docs.description: Represents a context channel that applications can join to share context data.

docs.title: DesktopAgent
docs.description: An FDC3 Desktop Agent is a desktop component (or aggregate of components) that serves as an orchestrator for applications in its domain.

docs.title: Errors
docs.description: FDC3 API operations may sometimes result in an error, which must be returned to the caller. Errors should be returned by rejecting the promise returned by the API with a JavaScript Error object (or equivalent for the language of the implementation). The Error Object's message should be chosen from the appropriate Error enumeration below.

docs.title: Globals
docs.description: Since FDC3 is typically available to the whole web application, desktop agents are expected to make the DesktopAgent interface available at a global level.

docs.title: Metadata
docs.description: FDC3 API operations return various types of metadata.

docs.title: PrivateChannel
docs.description: Object representing a private context channel, which is intended to support secure communication between applications, and extends the Channel interface with event handlers which provide information on the connection state of both parties, ensuring that desktop agents do not need to queue or retain messages that are broadcast before a context listener is added and that applications are able to stop broadcasting messages when the other party has disconnected.

docs.title: Types
docs.description: FDC3 API operations make use of several type declarations.

docs.title: API Overview (next)
docs.description: The role of FDC3 API is to establish a baseline interface for interoperability between applications. Because FDC3 is largely an agreement between existing platforms and applications, standards should be optimized for ease of adoption rather than functional completeness. Functionality absent from a FDC3 specification is in no way a commentary on its importance.

docs.title: App Directory Overview (next)
docs.description: An application directory (appD) is a structured repository of information about apps that can be used in an FDC3-enabled desktop. In other words, it’s a convenient way of storing and managing metadata about apps in your ecosystem.

docs.title: Context Data (next)
docs.description: To interoperate, apps need to exchange commonly recognized context structures that can indicate topic with any number of identifiers or mappings to different systems. FDC3 Context Data defines a standard for passing common identifiers and data between apps to create a seamless workflow. FDC3 Context Data is not a symbology solution and is not specifically focused on modeling financial objects. The focus is on providing a standard payload structure that can be used to establish a lowest common denominator for interoperability.
